<br>
You'll get minimum wage plus a cut of the tips, usually 10% of the take.  For me that was usually at least an extra $5 a night even on the slowest night, usually closer to $10 or $12 or more.<br>
<br>
Where I worked (a country club restaurant) I got a free meal whenever I worked, though I'd have to eat it early (before shift) or late (after shift).  But I could have whatever I wanted, from burgers to the night's special (usually a steak of some kind or baked chicken).  I also had free drinks on a continuous basis.  After talking to a few friends, I realize this was exceptional - usually you just get a food discount, but it still adds up.<br>
<br>
If you bus tables now, you'll learn how to be a good waiter and maybe move up the food chain, or at least have a better shot of waiting tables when you're able to serve alcohol legally, which varies by state.<br>
<br>
It was hard sometimes, and it was always at night and on the weekends, but I made good money.  I started at 16 and stayed until I was almost 18, and didn't regret it.<br>
<br>
